Let me just show you one thing.

00:55:19.330 --> 00:55:20.630
&gt;&gt; Male #2: Thank you.

00:55:20.630 --> 00:55:21.990
&gt;&gt; Jeffrey: Yeah.

00:55:21.990 --> 00:55:25.930
Actually, let me show you one thing.

00:55:25.930 --> 00:55:28.089
We watch
a lot of TV in this country.

00:55:28.089 --> 00:55:31.690
That's a little bit of a
distraction, but I think it actually is part

00:55:31.690 --> 00:55:34.160
of our
distraction as well.

00:55:34.160 --> 00:55:41.560
And the countries that I really
like are on the -- well, Italy, that's interesting.

00:55:41.560 --> 00:55:43.619
[laughter]

00:55:43.619 --> 00:55:44.940
But okay.

00:55:44.940 --> 00:55:51.359
Let me show you the -- 
here's the

00:55:51.359 --> 00:55:54.700
big difference of what happened in this country.

00:55:54.700 --> 00:56:01.079
And
what happened in the rest of -- in other places.

00:56:01.079 --> 00:56:05.410
So
basically, on the left-hand side is the change

00:56:05.410 --> 00:56:11.970
--
arithmetic change -- of tax to GNP ratio compared

00:56:11.970 --> 00:56:17.010
to 2008
minus 1965.

00:56:17.010 --> 00:56:21.540
So it's the rise of the tax share of
national income.

00:56:21.540 --> 00:56:26.710
And you can see that every high income
country has higher tax collections as a share

00:56:26.710 --> 00:56:32.070
of GNP than
the mid 1960s except for one country.

00:56:32.070 --> 00:56:33.609
That's us all the
way at the end.

00:56:33.609 --> 00:56:38.420
We're the only country that resisted
raising revenues in this country.

00:56:38.420 --> 00:56:40.570
That's the whole story that
I'm talking about.

00:56:40.570 --> 00:56:43.700
We decided we're not going to pay for
government.

00:56:43.700 --> 00:56:45.790
Everyone else pays for government.

00:56:45.790 --> 00:56:49.600
And the
social democracies had very -- they were already

00:56:49.600 --> 00:56:51.890
high and
they had big increases.

00:56:51.890 --> 00:56:56.170
The result was that the United
States, for example, just in one category

00:56:56.170 --> 00:56:58.480
-- social
spending -- this includes some of the transfer

00:56:58.480 --> 00:56:59.890
programs.

00:56:59.890 --> 00:57:03.940
We have the lowest level of social spending
of any

00:57:03.940 --> 00:57:04.940
country.

00:57:04.940 --> 00:57:09.240
This is basically Medicare/Medicaid, Social
Security, food stamps.

00:57:09.240 --> 00:57:16.859
Sweden, Denmark, Belgium, Austria,
France -- they're 10 percentage points of

00:57:16.859 --> 00:57:19.470
GDP higher than
we are.

00:57:19.470 --> 00:57:23.350
The countries that I really admire most in
their

00:57:23.350 --> 00:57:29.950
performance are Netherlands, Sweden, Finland
-- Norway,

00:57:29.950 --> 00:57:36.600
Sweden, Finland, Denmark, Netherlands, Germany.

00:57:36.600 --> 00:57:40.120
In
general, they're spending 10 percent of GDP

00:57:40.120 --> 00:57:42.060
more than
the United States.

00:57:42.060 --> 00:57:47.240
They're taxing about 15 percentage
points of GDP more than the United States,

00:57:47.240 --> 00:57:50.490
because they
also don't run a budget deficit.

00:57:50.490 --> 00:57:54.920
So they're spending a
lot and they're paying their way.

00:57:54.920 --> 00:57:57.900
And life is really
nice in those countries by the way.

00:57:57.900 --> 00:58:00.299
There's no poverty.

00:58:00.299 --> 00:58:03.040
Everybody gets five or six weeks of paid vacation.

00:58:03.040 --> 00:58:05.180
Of
course, it's paid within the context of their

00:58:05.180 --> 00:58:07.339
jobs and
the state.

00:58:07.339 --> 00:58:12.400
Everybody gets maternity and paternity leave
for several months.

00:58:12.400 --> 00:58:14.440
Nobody gets super rich.

00:58:14.440 --> 00:58:17.109
There's
some inherited wealth, but nobody gets super

00:58:17.109 --> 00:58:18.109
rich.

00:58:18.109 --> 00:58:20.619
That's the price that they pay.

00:58:20.619 --> 00:58:27.619
That's what they want,
which is a society of high affluence, very

00:58:27.619 --> 00:58:36.170
superb
education, very competitive industries, internationally

00:58:36.170 --> 00:58:40.240
competitive industries, highly innovative.

00:58:40.240 --> 00:58:43.410
They pay a
lot of government spending for the innovation.

00:58:43.410 --> 00:58:46.770
So Sweden
invests very heavily of public funds as well

00:58:46.770 --> 00:58:50.030
as having
companies like Ericsson and others that are

00:58:50.030 --> 00:58:54.180
doing private
sector innovation.

00:58:54.180 --> 00:59:04.359
And they paid for it basically by --
our taxes are, right now, 27 percent of GDP.

00:59:04.359 --> 00:59:07.799
In the normal
time before 2008 were our taxes were about

00:59:07.799 --> 00:59:10.880
30 percent of
GDP.

00:59:10.880 --> 00:59:15.820
Sweden, Denmark, Norway, Finland, Netherlands
about 45

00:59:15.820 --> 00:59:17.620
percent of GDP.

00:59:17.620 --> 00:59:21.039
It's a whole different environment.

00:59:21.039 --> 00:59:23.849
The
main difference by the way is that in those

00:59:23.849 --> 00:59:28.540
countries
there's a lot of support for families.

00:59:28.540 --> 00:59:30.039
There's day care.

00:59:30.039 --> 00:59:32.020
There's maternity leave.

00:59:32.020 --> 00:59:37.040
There's help for low skilled
households.

00:59:37.040 --> 00:59:41.069
There's early childhood development support.

00:59:41.069 --> 00:59:44.960
There's more investment for poor children
in schooling.

00:59:44.960 --> 00:59:50.440
They don't let anyone fall away.

00:59:50.440 --> 00:59:56.740
And the result is
evident when you live there as I have in Sweden

00:59:56.740 --> 01:00:00.180
or when
you visit, which is infrastructure is very

01:00:00.180 --> 01:00:03.210
well
maintained, education levels are uniformly

01:00:03.210 --> 01:00:06.960
high, there
are no pockets of poverty and there's very

01:00:06.960 --> 01:00:08.819
high social
mobility.

01:00:08.819 --> 01:00:13.140
Whereas, by the way the other shocking thing
about the United States -- let me show you

01:00:13.140 --> 01:00:14.289
one more
graph.

01:00:14.289 --> 01:00:17.089
I'm going to have to stop, also, and I know
you do

01:00:17.089 --> 01:00:19.760
as well.

01:00:19.760 --> 01:00:25.930
This is a graph showing the correlation of
parental educational attainment and children's

01:00:25.930 --> 01:00:29.670
educational attainment in the OECD countries.

01:00:29.670 --> 01:00:36.170
So a high
correlation means of course highly educated

01:00:36.170 --> 01:00:39.839
parents raise
children who end up with high educational

01:00:39.839 --> 01:00:40.839
attainment.

01:00:40.839 --> 01:00:44.480
Low education parents end up the opposite.

01:00:44.480 --> 01:00:48.099
The countries
over on the left with the lowest correlation

01:00:48.099 --> 01:00:52.230
or as
shorthand very high educational mobility

01:00:52.230 --> 01:00:58.220
intergenerationally -- Finland, Iceland, Norway,
Canada.

01:00:58.220 --> 01:01:04.280
The United States actually has the highest
intergenerational correlation at this point.

01:01:04.280 --> 01:01:08.310
So we pride
ourselves as being very highly socially mobile.

01:01:08.310 --> 01:01:10.589
But if
you're born to a family where your parents

01:01:10.589 --> 01:01:13.369
don't have
a high school degree the chance that you're

01:01:13.369 --> 01:01:17.180
going to
graduate Bachelor's degree in this country,

01:01:17.180 --> 01:01:20.170
probably under
10%.

01:01:20.170 --> 01:01:21.349
You just can't make it.

01:01:21.349 --> 01:01:25.760
The combination of
the poverty, the lack of social support, the

01:01:25.760 --> 01:01:29.940
neighborhood
factors, the intra-familial factors.

01:01:29.940 --> 01:01:32.349
The high tuition
rates.

01:01:32.349 --> 01:01:35.839
So this is why we're ending up really as the
most

01:01:35.839 --> 01:01:39.309
stratified of all of these countries.

01:01:39.309 --> 01:01:43.400
Because we don't
invest in any of this equalization.

01:01:43.400 --> 01:01:47.510
And that I think is
going to be our killer.

01:01:47.510 --> 01:01:52.450
The data just came out -- if
you're a Hispanic young man in this country

01:01:52.450 --> 01:02:00.789
-- 25 to
29 -- only 11 percent have a Bachelor's degree.

01:02:00.789 --> 01:02:06.760
African-American young man -- 25 to 29 -- 16
percent.

01:02:06.760 --> 01:02:09.430
In
this society, in a world economy, what kind

01:02:09.430 --> 01:02:14.490
of incomes,
jobs, life prospects does that mean?

01:02:14.490 --> 01:02:17.350
Very poor.

01:02:17.350 --> 01:02:18.839
Very
unstable.

01:02:18.839 --> 01:02:20.829
Very erratic.

01:02:20.829 --> 01:02:22.380
And you know?

01:02:22.380 --> 01:02:24.710
Some people say
that's fine.

01:02:24.710 --> 01:02:30.730
But I think what it's going to mean for the
corrosion of our society is extremely serious.

01:02:30.730 --> 01:02:33.670
And I
think the process is already begun.

01:02:33.670 --> 01:02:37.119
And it wouldn't take
a revolution to correct this.

01:02:37.119 --> 01:02:41.540
It would just take a few
percent of GDP to correct it.

01:02:41.540 --> 01:02:42.900
That's the beauty of it.

01:02:42.900 --> 01:02:44.920
And the question is, "are we going to wait
till there is

01:02:44.920 --> 01:02:50.670
an explosion or are we actually going to correct
it?"

01:02:50.670 --> 01:02:54.920
I
was reading last night about the Bonus Army

01:02:54.920 --> 01:02:59.170
in the Great
Depression when the veterans were demanding

01:02:59.170 --> 01:03:03.240
some help in
1932.

01:03:03.240 --> 01:03:05.940
Hoover sent in the troops.

01:03:05.940 --> 01:03:09.490
And many people were
killed and wounded.

01:03:09.490 --> 01:03:18.900
And then, in 1933, they struck again
and Roosevelt sent Eleanor Roosevelt to the

01:03:18.900 --> 01:03:20.119
camp.

01:03:20.119 --> 01:03:24.349
And
she discussed and negotiated with them and

01:03:24.349 --> 01:03:27.730
they made a
program so that the veterans would get jobs

01:03:27.730 --> 01:03:32.369
in the CCC,
the Civilian Conservation Corps.

01:03:32.369 --> 01:03:35.369
And the line that came
out of it was "Hoover sent the troops and

01:03:35.369 --> 01:03:37.820
Roosevelt sent
his wife".

01:03:37.820 --> 01:03:41.130
And it's the kind of society we want.

01:03:41.130 --> 01:03:43.299
If
we're clearing the parks with police with

01:03:43.299 --> 01:03:46.580
batons, we're
going to end up in the Hoover world.

01:03:46.580 --> 01:03:50.549
And, if we send the
Eleanor Roosevelts of the world and try to

01:03:50.549 --> 01:03:52.500
figure out
something, we're going to end up with some

01:03:52.500 --> 01:03:53.500
decency.

01:03:53.500 --> 01:03:54.500
Thank you very much.

